37) Final One-Paragraph Summary
JavaScript exists to add behavior and interactivity to the web. The JS engine exists to parse and execute code. Execution contexts exist so running code has a structured environment for variables, scope, and this. Scope and scope chain exist to control visibility and allow nested access predictably. Closures exist so functions can retain outer data. The call stack exists to manage execution order. Because JS is single-threaded, browser APIs and the event loop exist to handle async tasks without blocking everything. The DOM exists so JS can manipulate the page as objects, and the rendering pipeline exists so those changes can become visible UI. So from a frontend UI update perspective, the flow is: browser captures event → queues callback → event loop schedules it → JS runs handler in a new execution context → state/DOM changes happen → browser re-renders the updated UI.

